context: The term "house music" is said to have originated from a <a1_0><b6_0>Chicago<b6_0/><a1_0/> club called <a0_0>The Warehouse<a0_0/>, which existed from <a2_0><b7_0>1977 to 1983<b7_0/><a2_0/>. Clubbers to The Warehouse were <a3_0><b8_0>primarily black and gay<b8_0/><a3_0/>, who came to dance to music played by the club's resident DJ <a4_0><b9_0>Frankie Knuckles<b9_0/><a4_0/>, whom fans refer to as the "godfather of house". After the Warehouse closed in 1983, the crowds went to Knuckles' new club, The Power Plant. In the Channel 4 documentary Pump Up The Volume, Knuckles remarks that the first time he heard the term "house music" was upon seeing "we play house music" on a sign in the window of a bar on Chicago's South Side. One of the people in the car with him joked, "you know, that's the kind of music you play down at <b5_0>the Warehouse<b5_0/>!", and then everybody laughed. South-Side Chicago DJ Leonard "Remix" Roy, in self-published statements, claims he put such a sign in a tavern window because it was where he played music that one might find in one's home; in his case, it referred to his mother's soul & disco records, which he worked into his sets. Farley Jackmaster Funk was quoted as saying "In 1982, I was DJing at a club called The Playground and there was this kid named Leonard 'Remix' Roy who was a DJ at a rival club called The Rink.
